## Design and architecture notes

- **Why Quarto + OJS.** Quarto renders to a plain static site (ideal for GitHub
  Pages) and keeps content, styling, and logic in one maintainable repo. OJS is
  used for its strengths: loading the CSV (`FileAttachment(...).csv()`) and
  embedding the interactive component.
- **Why the quiz is one vanilla-JS component, not many reactive OJS cells.** A
  quiz is inherently *stateful* — current question, running score, locked
  answers. Observable's reactive model is built for dataflow (recompute when
  inputs change), which is awkward for step-by-step mutable state. So the quiz
  engine is a single self-contained DOM component (built with plain JavaScript
  and a closure over its state) inside one OJS cell that depends only on the
  loaded questions. This keeps the state model simple and predictable, and still
  lives entirely within the Quarto/OJS setup. If you later wanted zero Quarto
  dependency, this same component would port to a plain `index.html` +
  `quiz.js` + `d3.csv` with almost no change.
- **One question at a time.** Immediate per-question feedback is the core of a
  self-assessment learning tool, so questions are shown singly rather than in
  batches — the explanation lands at the teachable moment.
- **Accessibility.** Native form controls (radios/checkboxes) and buttons for
  keyboard navigation; visible focus rings; results conveyed by icon **and**
  text, never colour alone; `aria-live` feedback region; contrast chosen for
  WCAG AA; honours `prefers-reduced-motion`.
- **Session length.** If more than 15 questions match the chosen filters, a
  random 15 are asked (constant `MAX_QUESTIONS` in `index.qmd`); the user is
  told how many of the pool are being used.

